Charles P. Rettig of California has been nominated to be the Commissioner of Internal Revenue for the remainder of a five-year term beginning on November 13, 2017. Rettig has over 35 years of professional experience and has represented numerous taxpayers before the Internal Revenue Service, the U.S. Department of Justice, and other taxing authorities. He has served as Chair of the IRS Advisory Council and as a Member of the Advisory Board for the California Franchise Tax Board. Rettig is currently vice-chair of the taxation section of the American Bar Association and vice-president of the American College of Tax Counsel. He is a certified specialist in taxation law, estate planning, and trust and probate law. Rettig holds an LL.M. in taxation from New York University School of Law, a J.D. degree from Pepperdine University, and a B.A. in economics from UCLA.